Next.js is a flexible React framework used to build fast, full-stack web applications. While React is a library focused on the user interface (UI), Next.js builds on top of it to handle complex production requirements like routing, data fetching, and performance optimizations out of the box. [1, 2, 3, 4] 
## Key Features
Next.js provides several built-in tools that simplify development and improve user experience: [1, 5, 6, 7] 

* Rendering Options: You can choose how your content is delivered based on your needs:
* Server-Side Rendering (SSR): Generates HTML on each request, which is great for dynamic content and SEO.
   * Static Site Generation (SSG): Pre-renders pages at build time for near-instant loading.
   * Incremental Static Regeneration (ISR): Allows you to update static content without rebuilding the entire site.
* File-Based Routing: Instead of using external libraries like React Router, you simply add files to the app or pages directory to create new routes automatically.
* Full-Stack Capabilities: Through API Routes and Server Actions, you can write backend code (like database queries) directly within your project, eliminating the need for a separate server.
* Optimisations: It includes automatic code splitting, which only loads the necessary JavaScript for the current page, and a built-in <Image> component for automatic image resizing and lazy loading. [1, 3, 4, 5, 8, 9, 10, 11, 12] 

## Why Developers Use It
Next.js is often preferred over "plain" React for production-ready apps because it solves common issues like poor SEO and slow initial load times. It is widely used by major companies such as Netflix, TikTok, Uber, and Nike. [8, 13, 14, 15] 
Developed and maintained by Vercel, it continues to evolve with recent versions like Next.js 16 introducing faster build tools like Turbopack and deeper integration with AI coding agents. [14, 16] 
